mbered rules. Deny wins over allow/bypass. Order: deny → allow/bypass → risk fallback.\n\nWait, the spec says order: deny → allow/bypass → risk fallback. So I should check all remembered rules: if any deny matches → auto-deny. Else if any allow/bypass matches → auto-allow. Else risk fallback.\n\nLet me write patterns.ts:\n\n```ts\nexport function matchKey(name: string, args: unknown): string {\n  let salient = '';\n  if (typeof args === 'object' && args !== null) {\n    const rec = args as Record<string, unknown>;\n    const p = rec['path'];\n    const d = rec['dir'];\n    if (typeof p === 'string') salient = p;\n    else if (typeof d === 'string') salient = d;\n  }\n  return `${name}:${salient}`;\n}\n\nexport function matchesPattern(pattern: string, key: string): boolean {\n  let p = pattern;\n  if (!p.includes(':')) {\n    p = `${p}:*`;\n  }\n  // escape regex metachars except *\n  let re = '';\n  for (const ch of p) {\n    if (ch === '*') re += '.*';\n    else re += ch.replace(/[.*+?^${}()|[\\]\\\\]/g, '\\\\$&');\n  }\n  const r = new RegExp(`^${re}$`);\n  return r.test(key);\n}\n```\n\nWait, the escape regex inside the loop - I'm replacing per char. Let me just check if char is a regex metachar. Actually simpler: build string with escaping.\n\nLet me rewrite:\n```ts\nexport function matchesPattern(pattern: string, key: string): boolean {\n  let p = pattern;\n  if (!p.includes(':')) {\n    p = `${p}:*`;\n  }\n  let re = '';\n  for (const ch of p) {\n    if (ch === '*') {\n      re += '.*';\n    } else if (/[.*+?^${}()|[\\]\\\\]/.test(ch)) {\n      re += '\\\\' + ch;\n    } else {\n      re += ch;\n    }\n  }\n  return new RegExp(`^${re}$`).test(key);\n}\n```\n\npolicy.ts:\n\n```ts\nimport type { PermissionPolicy, PermissionPolicyOptions } from '../core/contracts';\nimport type { RiskLevel, PermissionDecision } from '../core/events';\nimport { matchKey, matchesPattern } from './patterns';\n\nexport function createPermissionPolicy(opts?: PermissionPolicyOptions): PermissionPolicy {\n  const autoAllowSafe = opts?.autoAllowSafe ?? true;\n  const rules = new Map<string, PermissionDecision>();\n  if (opts?.initial) {\n    for (const { pattern, decision } of opts.initial) {\n      if (decision === 'allow-once') continue;\n      rules.set(pattern, decision);\n    }\n  }\n  return {\n    evaluate(name, args, risk) {\n      const key = matchKey(name, args);\n      let deny = false;\n      let allow = false;\n      for (const [pattern, decision] of rules) {\n        if (!matchesPattern(pattern, key)) continue;\n        if (decision === 'deny') { deny = true; }\n        else if (decision === 'always-allow-pattern' || decision === 'dangerous-bypass') { allow = true; }\n      }\n      if (deny) return 'auto-deny';\n      if (allow) return 'auto-allow';\n      switch (risk) {\n        case 'safe': return autoAllowSafe ? 'auto-allow' : 'prompt';\n        case 'risky': return 'prompt';\n        case 'dangerous': return 'prompt';\n      }\n    },\n    remember(pattern, decision) {\n      if (decision === 'allow-once') return;\n      rules.set(pattern, decision);\n    }\n  };\n}\n```\n\nWait, the contracts.ts file - I need to import `PermissionPolicy` and `PermissionPolicyOptions` from it. The brief says \"import types ONLY from `../core/contracts` (the `PermissionPolicy` interface you implement — annotate the factory's return type with it) and `../core/events` (`RiskLevel`, `PermissionDecision`).\"\n\nBut `PermissionPolicyOptions` is also defined in contracts.ts per the brief. Let me import it too. The brief shows it as part of the interface this unit exposes, frozen in contracts.ts. So it's there.\n\nLet me also handle the exhaustive switch - with strict mode and noFallthroughCasesInSwitch, the switch is fine. But TS might complain that not all code paths return. Let me add a default or make it exhaustive. Since RiskLevel is a union of 3 literals and I cover all 3, TS should be fine if I have all cases. Actually TS may still complain because it doesn't know the switch is exhaustive without a never check. Let me add a default that returns 'prompt' or use the never pattern.\n\nActually with strict union types and all cases covered, TS control flow analysis knows the switch is exhaustive and the function returns. Let me verify... yes, TS 4.x+ handles this correctly when the switch covers all union cases.\n\nNow tests. Let me write them per requirements.\n\nLet me also double check: \"A bare tool-name pattern (no `:`) should match any call to that tool (treat `write_file` as `write_file:*`).\" - handled.\n\nTest for `read_file:src/*` matches `read_file:src/a.ts` but not `read_file:lib/a.ts`. With my regex: `read_file:src/.*` → matches `read_file:src/a.ts` ✓, doesn't match `read_file:lib/a.ts` ✓.\n\nBut wait, what about `read_file:src/*` matching `read_file:src/sub/a.ts`? `.*` matches `sub/a.ts` so yes. That's fine.\n\nLet me write the tests now.\n\n```ts\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\nimport { createPermissionPolicy } from '../src/permissions/policy';\nimport { matchKey, matchesPattern } from '../src/permissions/patterns';\n\ndescribe('permissions policy', () => {\n  it('auto-allows safe by default', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    expect(p.evaluate('read_file', { path: 'a' }, 'safe')).toBe('auto-allow');\n  });\n  it('prompts safe when autoAllowSafe false', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy({ autoAllowSafe: false });\n    expect(p.evaluate('read_file', { path: 'a' }, 'safe')).toBe('prompt');\n  });\n  it('prompts risky', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    expect(p.evaluate('write_file', { path: 'x' }, 'risky')).toBe('prompt');\n  });\n  it('prompts dangerous with no remembered rule', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    expect(p.evaluate('rm', { path: 'x' }, 'dangerous')).toBe('prompt');\n  });\n  it('remembered always-allow-pattern auto-allows', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    p.remember('write_file:*', 'always-allow-pattern');\n    expect(p.evaluate('write_file', { path: 'x.txt' }, 'risky')).toBe('auto-allow');\n  });\n  it('remembered deny wins over broader allow', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    p.remember('write_file:*', 'always-allow-pattern');\n    p.remember('write_file:secret.txt', 'deny');\n    expect(p.evaluate('write_file', { path: 'secret.txt' }, 'risky')).toBe('auto-deny');\n  });\n  it('allow-once is a no-op', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    p.remember('write_file:*', 'allow-once');\n    expect(p.evaluate('write_file', { path: 'x' }, 'risky')).toBe('prompt');\n  });\n  it('dangerous-bypass pre-grants dangerous', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    p.remember('rm:*', 'dangerous-bypass');\n    expect(p.evaluate('rm', { path: 'x' }, 'dangerous')).toBe('auto-allow');\n  });\n  it('deterministic across calls', () => {\n    const p = createPermissionPolicy();\n    p.remember('write_file:*', 'always-allow-pattern');\n    for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {\n      expect(p.evaluate('write_file', { path: 'x' }, 'risky')).toBe('auto-allow');\n    }\n  });\n});\n\ndescribe('patterns', () => {\n  it('matchKey uses path', () => {\n    expect(matchKey('write_file', { path: 'a.txt' })).toBe('write_file:a.txt');\n  });\n  it('matchKey uses dir fallback', () => {\n    expect(matchKey('ls', { dir: 'src' })).toBe('ls:src');\n  });\n  it('matchKey empty for non-object', () => {\n    expect(matchKey('x', null)).toBe('x:');\n    expect(matchKey('x', undefined)).toBe('x:');\n    expect(matchKey('x', 'str')).toBe('x:');\n  });\n  it('glob matches', () => {\n    expect(matchesPattern('write_file:*', 'write_file:anything')).toBe(true);\n    expect(matchesPattern('read_file:src/*', 'read_file:src/a.ts')).toBe(true);\n    expect(matchesPattern('read_file:src/*', 'read_file:lib/a.ts')).toBe(false);\n  });\n  it('bare tool name matches any', () => {\n    expect(matchesPattern('write_file', 'write_file:anything')).toB